      <hedline>
        <hl1>Inroads of Accessibility</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Dorothy Kerzner Lipsky letter, commenting on August 17 article on handicapped who climbed White Mountains of New Hampshire in wheelchairs and on crutches, says it raises questions about continuing exclusion of people with disabilities from many areas of life</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''For These Trailblazers, Wheelchairs Matter'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''For These Trailblazers, Wheelchairs Matter'' (front page, Aug. 17):</p>
        <p>I read with admiration your article about the people who climbed New Hampshire's White Mountains in wheelchairs and on crutches. Yet the article also raises questions about the continuing exclusion of people with disabilities from many areas of life.</p>
        <p>It should not be necessary for people with disabilities to enlist a cadre of friends to enjoy our common heritage, the wilderness. As a society, we can choose to exclude millions of our fellow Americans or to make those accommodations and modifications that will preclude impairments from becoming disabilities.</p>
        <p>DOROTHY KERZNER LIPSKY  New York, Aug. 18, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is director, National Center on Educational Restructuring and Inclusion, CUNY Graduate Center.</p>
      </block>
